shared_text:
The Watkins Warriors
August 31 at 9:26 AM ·

Fellow Warriors,

We want to thank all of our parents, families, and loyal fans in the community for your patience and understanding as we navigate the strict limitations on our ticketed athletic events.
The Governor's recent order restricting attendance to only parents (other immediate family when seating is available) and only 15% of fixed seating capacity has made for challenging circumstances to say the least.

Our ticketing plan under these restraints for 2020 fall sports is as follows:

· Parents of students participating in the events will have priority when buying their tickets
· Students will be not be permitted, unless:
· they are participating in a different…

As we continue to learn more information regarding planning for the 2020-2021 school year, we are committed to keeping our families informed. Please find attached a Facts in a Flash document which outlines important information for the upcoming school year. Additional information will be provided as it becomes available.

Facts in a Flash
https://filecabinet.eschoolview.com/011218FA-4E8E-4C20-AE4D-005C63AE5A3F/FactsinaFlash.pdf

Should you have questions for the District, please complete this form:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScU0k2Y_5IrSIjtY3PDQC0TNQdy36WU9y7x3IK_UhFjDaKSbQ/viewform

If you have not already done so, please complete the Back to School Form to allow for planning for the 2020-2021 school year:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSf_ycqSwnDgS4PPjUv-KwMisvRDTo5JfZSZbEB8JU2wSBdrNQ/viewform

Thank you for your continued patience as we work through all of the changes.

post_text:
We need your feedback!

As we continue to plan for the unknown, we would like some information from our families. Governor DeWine and state education officials have mentioned several possibilities for schools in Ohio next year, including continued remote learning or a mix of remote and in-person learning. We know that the world is changing quickly with new information being introduced daily, so please answer the questions on the survey to the best of your ability with the information you have today based on your family situation. We will use this information to help guide our planning for the future.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSd0bwn3nBGmLjqlcoIkoHAco7hiFohqsL5ze5oWqDRkpEeLZQ/viewform

post_text: Katie and her fellow seniors Hannah and Emma have done a fantastic job organizing blood drives at WMHS for three years. Let's help make their last drive their best!
shared_text:
Katie Bryant‎The City of Pataskala's Community Group
May 8 at 12:05 AM ·

Hi everyone! I help run the blood drives at Watkins Memorial and we are doing a community drive for our last one of the year. We are in need of donors 16 and up. You don’t have to be a student to donate, the more the merrier. Message me for more details or to sign up :)) Sign up directly at the link below!

https://www.redcrossblood.org/give.html/drive-results?zipSponsor=WMHS

It’s on May 20th from 10-4 at the Pataskala YMCA :))

post_text:
A message from the local food pantry:

The Storehouse pantry received more generous donations today of food items and diapers. We have been so blessed with the generosity of the community. Again, if you or someone you know has a need for food the Storehouse for Jesus is open and we are there to serve. We are still using drive-up curb service. The hours of operation are:

Tuesday’s 10:00 to 12:00
Thursday evenings 6:00 to 8:00

We are usually closed on the 5th Thursday but during this time of need we will be open every Thursday.

https://www.facebook.com/storehouseforjesusfoodpantry/

Storehouse for Jesus Food Pantry is at Pataskala Church of the Nazarene.
March 23 at 7:02 PM · Pataskala, OH ·

The Storehouse for Jesus food pantry will continue to be open during the stay at home order. With so many people now out of work the need is even stronger. If you need help with groceries or know someone that does, we are here to serve you. We are pre-boxing the food and working on a curbside service. Just drive up to the Storehouse, stay in your car, we will come out and get your information, load your groceries and you’re on your way. Praying this coronavirus passes soon and the doors will be opened again. We miss praying and talking with the families. The clothing section remains closed until all restrictions are lifted and we can open the doors. Praying for everyone to stay healthy.
Storehouse hours:
Tuesday's 10AM - 12PM
Thursday evenings - 6PM - 8PM

God Bless

Pataskala Community Outreach will continue to assist with student meals as often as we can. We are relying on donation as well as volunteers so this ability can change from day to day. In an effort to keep our volunteers, and all of the families we serve, as healthy and unexposed as possible- we will be switching to a delivery method with a porch drop off. In order to reach all of the families in need, we will need you to fill out a form- so we can add you to our distribution list.

Our first deliveries are scheduled for Monday March 23rd and is sponsored by Cazuelas Mexican Restaurant & Cantina! We will also include a food supplementary bag to hold the family over for a few days until the next delivery.

Please visit www.pataskalaoutreach.org/find-a-free-meal to sign up for meals.

Good Afternoon,

Per the order of Governor DeWine, students will not be reporting to school beginning March 17th through April 3rd . While this continues to be a very fluid situation, as of now, the District is planning to be in school Friday, March 13th and Monday, March 16th .

We are developing a plan and compiling resources for our families during this extended closure. While we don't have all of the details right now, we are expecting additional guidance as we navigate through this process.

As of today, March 12th, all events and parent meetings are canceled. Additional information will be forthcoming from individual buildings.

Respectfully,

Kasey Perkins
Superintendent

post_text:
Dear SWL Families,

It is with great sadness that I inform you of the loss of a freshman at Watkins Memorial High School, through a tragic accident. It is very difficult for all of us to process the death of a young person. It is sure to raise many emotions, concerns and questions from our community and especially our students.

Monday, a support team of counselors and psychologists from surrounding school districts, will be on hand at the high school and middle school to provide counseling and support to our students.

The district extends our heartfelt and deepest sympathies to the families. We will continue to work with all families and students during this tragedy.

Please respect these families and their privacy through this very difficult time.

Sincerely,

Kasey Perkins
Superintendent

post_text:
Can you believe that we are 12 months away from opening our new Watkins Intermediate School? With this excitement comes change to the school calendar for next year due to students moving mid-year and the need to vacate the current high school for renovations. While we understand that changes in the calendar effect family schedules, we need the extra time during the winter to make the transition to the new building successful and positive for our staff and students. Our district will be in a transition period over the next several years as the new buildings come to completion and renovations are done.

2020-2021 Calendar:http://www.swl.k12.oh.us/Downloads/2020-2021%20School%20Calendar.pdf

Timeline of Events for the Building Project:http://www.swl.k12.oh.us/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=632P2YI&dasi=3230

shared_text:
James George‎PATASKALA
November 21, 2019 at 3:37 PM ·

Local Teacher receives award by Jim George.

The Southwest Licking Schools Education Foundation is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization which provides funding and/or materials for projects that advance the curriculum of the Southwest Licking School District. We started last January by awarding each school building with an impact gift (STEM/Technology carts) to let people know who we are and what we do. We just finished our first cycle of grant reviews where teachers submitted funding requests for various materials to enhance their curriculum. The group reviewed several requests and selected a recipient for funding. Ms. Margret Savage of Watkins Middle School received the award during her 4th period class. Ms. Savage requested funding for pianos for her classroom and has some wonderful ideas on enhancing students' access to piano lessons.

Pictured L-R : Lauren Montagnese, Cathy Spindler, Leslie Space, Margaret Savage, Dan Hayes and Amy Hoovier.

shared_text:
Watkins Memorial High School
August 30, 2019 at 2:44 PM ·

Have you heard about our Drug Free Club?

Watkins Memorial High School students are invited to apply for membership in the Drug Free Club. The purposes of the club are to:
- reward students’ good choices and
- provide students with tools to help stay drug free.

How it Works
A student volunteers to join Drug Free Clubs of America, which requires passing a drug test and submitting a $20 annual membership fee. Members are eligible for school and community perks throughout the year. Random resting of members continues regularly, and as long as members remain drug free, the perks continue. If a student tests positive for drugs, parents receive a phone call directly from the doctor who analyzed the sample; club membership is placed on hold until the student regains active membership by passing a subsequent drug test. Parents are also provided with a list of community resources. Results are never shared with the school.

Apply online at https://drugfreeclubs.com/apply-for-membership/

post_text:
Watkins Memorial High School will be supporting students through an internship program for the 2019-2020 school year.

Program Requirements:
- Students must participate in a screening process and be interviewed before being granted an internship.
- Students are expected to complete 70 hours in a placement per semester.
- Internships could be a semester or year-long commitment.

Mentor Expectations:
- Sign a weekly time sheet for accountability.
- Complete a short evaluation each quarter for each intern.
- Provide meaningful opportunities for experience in a field of interest for each intern.

If you are interested in learning more about partnering with us for this program, please fill out the form below and we will contact you. We are looking for mentors in the fields listed below. If your field is not listed as a current need, please fill out the form and we will keep your information for future years.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfN1ph_MSqohCZsBLjDdOHzEwQeTnBNoVmrlPnMqWWKnfQ3Aw/viewform

Last week, thousands of students from around the world competed at the 2019 FIRST, For Inspiration and Recognition of Science and Technology, World Championship in Detroit, MI. The Crazy LEGO WarriorBots from Watkins Middle School were one of the the three teams representing Ohio. Our season started August 1st, 2018. Each team is challenged to create an innovative solution to a real world problem, unite as a team, as well as imagine, design, and program a LEGO EV3 Mindstorms robot to complete as many challenge missions in the 2.5 minute time limit.

This opportunity was more than competing in a robotics competition for our students. The Crazy LEGO WarriorBots strategized with the team from…

post_text:
On Friday April 26, 2019 members of Mr. Fife’s Engineering Design class took part in the annual Egg Drop contest at COTC. Students had to design an apparatus that would protect an egg from a 22 ft. drop onto a hard floor. In addition, the goal was to make it as light as possible and out of the fewest number of parts. The final challenge was to have the device land as close as possible to a bullseye on the ground.

Mckenzi Waspe went first and was successful. She wrapped an egg in bubble wrap and made a cardboard box held together with clear office tape. Jared Rice was next with his device made of drinking straws and duct tape. His drop did not go as planned. His device landed on its…
